The article discusses the devastating impact of the COVID-19 pandemic in Latin America and the Caribbean, where it has accounted for over 2.7 million deaths, more than 40% of global reported deaths. In response to this crisis, President Biden led leaders of the Americas in adopting an "Action Plan on Health and Resilience in the Americas." This plan aims to prevent, prepare for, and respond to future pandemic threats and improve the delivery of healthcare to vulnerable populations. To support the implementation of the Action Plan, the Biden Administration announced the Americas Health Corps, which will provide training to 500,000 healthcare professionals in the region within five years. The US government also emphasizes its commitment to ending the acute phase of the COVID-19 pandemic and promoting recovery in the Americas. Additionally, the Biden-Harris Administration aims to strengthen global health security by engaging with partners and expanding health security programs in the region.